snippet.textDisplay: Hi! Spaniard here. We call it "crema catalana" and I make it every week at the restaurant I work at. The way Julian did it wasn't actually correct but eih... as long as it tastes good, who cares? You have to put milk in a pot, (or in this case your vegan substitute) add cinnamon sticks and lemon/orange peels (just the skin, not the white part because that's bitter) let it boil but just for a minute. Cover the pot and leave it like that for 12 hours or just 15 min if you can't wait XD. But if you let it overnight it will taste better. Then remove the cinnamon and the peels, low heat and add corn starch to thicken it, maybe some blended cashews, nutritional yeast, and sugar (maybe some turmeric for the color) and mix it well.  Pour the crème into your ramekins, put them in the fridge and BAM! Also, for those of you who don't have a torch, use a spoon. Warm it up with a lighter or with your stove.
snippet.textOriginal: Hi! Spaniard here. We call it "crema catalana" and I make it every week at the restaurant I work at. The way Julian did it wasn't actually correct but eih... as long as it tastes good, who cares? You have to put milk in a pot, (or in this case your vegan substitute) add cinnamon sticks and lemon/orange peels (just the skin, not the white part because that's bitter) let it boil but just for a minute. Cover the pot and leave it like that for 12 hours or just 15 min if you can't wait XD. But if you let it overnight it will taste better. Then remove the cinnamon and the peels, low heat and add corn starch to thicken it, maybe some blended cashews, nutritional yeast, and sugar (maybe some turmeric for the color) and mix it well.  Pour the crème into your ramekins, put them in the fridge and BAM! Also, for those of you who don't have a torch, use a spoon. Warm it up with a lighter or with your stove.

snippet.textDisplay: Hey, in the future, brûlée your sugar before you put it on top of the crème. Once brûlée-d (or just caramelized), crush it up and then put the powder on top of the crème. Then use your torch to melt all the caramelized sugar back to one solid piece for you to break. This allows you to caramelize the sugar without burning it! I've done this before by putting sugar on a silicone baking mat and torching it. You can move swifter and should you burn some sugar, you can discard it!

snippet.textDisplay: in 2006, high school musical came out, which contained a line by zeke baylor about creme brulee: this creamy custard-like filling with a caramelized surface, which i've heard is really satisfying. and all 6 year old me wanted to do was try creme brulee. i looked up bakeries near me and my dad took me to two, neither of which had creme brulee. i then looked up recipes online and maybe it was the fact that i had a 3rd grade reading level but they all seemed way too advanced. I didn't get the chance to have creme brulee until 9 years later. needless to say, this title really came to punch me in the face. unsubscribed.

snippet.textDisplay: Hey if you ever wanna try more desserts, in Canada we have this fried pastry thing called beaver tails that you usually eat in the winter on a frozen lake with hot chocolate. The most common way to have it (and in my opinion the better tasting one) is with just sugar, cinnamon and a little bit of lemon but people have it with maple butter or chocolate with bananas too and you can put whatever you want on it. I think you and Jenna would really like it!
